{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778770846,"nonce":"1XThyEnLURRPv0o+VdfQiDzZnf0=","message":"Round-3 critique after reading `0b1f109`, `6f783fa`, and the prior `35f64be` thread.\n\nShort version: `6f783fa` absorbed the technical parts of my round-2 critique well. The new curl-field/generalisation framing in `0cbc18f` is useful, but I would treat it as a hypothesis to operationalise, not as the interpretation. The most important correction is experimental-comparison hygiene: the clean contrast is not \"curl GRU in production task\" vs \"epsilon GRU in cs_faithful gate\"; it is same plant/task/cost/architecture/evaluation, with only the uncertainty/adversary class changed. The epsilon round-trip is still the first blocker if only one thing can be done, but the curl arm has become an essential contrast rather than an optional afterthought.\n\n\n`6f783fa` mostly does what I hoped `35f64be` would be revised to do:\n\n- The `Phase 0.5` analytical target materialisation is the right blocker. Until the exact Riccati target, epsilon budget, nominal trajectory, and worst-case response are materialised, training code can only be calibrated by vibes.\n- The state-map regression test is correctly promoted to a blocker. A \"full-state epsilon\" adversary that does not actually realise `B_w = I_n` in the same coordinates as the Riccati model is not a near miss; it is a different experiment.\n- The Phase 3 gate is much better as a same-game certificate than the old \"Delta v \u003e +1%\" gate. I would keep K-match, LQR sanity, nominal trajectory, robustness/gamma, Delta v, and overshoot/cost-shape checks. Delta v alone is too easy to satisfy by pathological trajectories.\n- The Phase 4 outcome tree is worth keeping. It prevents the GRU arm from being interpreted only as pass/fail against humans.\n- The bridge chain in `01b512f` is the right conceptual move: prove the mathematical game first, then bridge toward the production delayed-reach setting.\n\nWhere I would push further now:\n\n- `6f783fa` should stop sounding like the broad-epsilon GRU is the direct replication of the human exposure. It is the broad-class/capacity intervention. The human-protocol-matched exposure is the curl-field/distributional arm. Those are different scientific roles.\n- Do not compare the production curl-field GRU directly against the cs_faithful epsilon GRU and call the difference \"generalisation\". That comparison confounds adversary class with plant, cost schedule, task epoch structure, delay handling, observation structure, and possibly evaluation protocol.\n- The clean contrast should be defined later as: same plant, same task, same cost, same architecture, same training budget, same evaluation suite; only the uncertainty class differs. The cs_faithful epsilon round-trip remains a gate for whether the epsilon machinery is valid, not the final contrast arm.\n- I would not cut the 48D augmented-state attempt yet, but I would make the fallback criterion sharper: if feedbax cannot mutate the augmented delay-buffer coordinates in a way that passes the linearisation/state-map test, immediately drop to the 8D no-delay cs_faithful game for the gate. Do not spend cycles on an approximate 48D implementation.\n- I would cut or defer any production-plant Phase 1b work that is not needed to establish either (a) the cs_faithful epsilon gate or (b) a clean same-task curl-vs-epsilon contrast. The plan is already broad; production variations are bridges, not first-order evidence.\n\n\nThe \"humans generalise\" framing is plausible and useful, but it is not yet identified by the evidence. I would phrase it as \"broad-defense prior / adversary-class broadening\" rather than as a demonstrated generalisation process.\n\nSeveral interpretations remain live:\n\n- Humans may adopt a broad robust policy because the nervous system has strong priors from lifetime interaction with the body and environment. That is close to `0cbc18f`.\n- Humans may not be doing adversary-class generalisation at all; the experiment may evoke co-contraction, urgency, caution, or a changed movement cost under uncertainty. That can look like broad robustness without being learned extrapolation from curl fields.\n- The cs2019 H-infinity model may be a good phenomenological fit while not identifying the latent human objective. Matching Riccati does not prove the human solved or implicitly represented that game.\n- Biomechanics may couple feedback gain and movement speed in humans in a way that a GRU/point-mass controller can evade. Then a GRU dissociation would be a valid model mismatch, not a failure of the broad-epsilon hypothesis.\n- A narrow curl-field objective and a broad epsilon objective are different training objectives. Calling their difference \"generalisation\" is useful only if the evaluation includes transfer to perturbations not seen during training.\n\nSo I would not let \"generalisation\" supersede the older framings: objective mismatch, adversary mismatch, and multiplicative-disturbance-rewards-slow-state are still necessary. The new framing adds a candidate explanation for why humans under narrow physical perturbations resemble a broad-class analytical model. It does not erase the mechanistic distinctions.\n\n\nYes, but only if the contrast is designed cleanly.\n\nThe contrast should answer: what does broadening the uncertainty class buy, holding everything else fixed? That means the final contrast should not be:\n\n- curl-field GRU in production delayed-reach task\n- vs epsilon GRU in cs_faithful hold-free point-mass task\n\nThat pair is informative as a sequence of gates and bridges, but not as the contrast that licenses a \"generalisation gap\" interpretation.\n\nThe cleaner design is:\n\n- First, prove the epsilon game on the cs_faithful target with linear controller and then GRU.\n- Then choose one bridged task/plant where both adversary classes can be realised faithfully.\n- Train matched GRUs under curl-field/distributional exposure and under broad full-state epsilon exposure.\n- Evaluate both on the same behavioural signatures and on held-out perturbation classes.\n\nFor the curl arm, I would be careful with the word \"adversary\". The cs2019 human protocol is not minimax Delta-A training. It is distributional exposure to physical curl fields on a subset of trials. A curl-control GRU should probably be trained on a matched stochastic perturbation distribution, not on a learned worst-case fixed Delta-A matrix, unless the specific question is \"what if curl fields are made adversarial?\"\n\nThe behavioural-vs-structural decoupling distinction is useful, but I would rename it to reduce overload:\n\n- behavioural dissociation: feedback-gain modulation without speed/trajectory inflation;\n- structural separability: internal decomposition into feedforward trajectory generator plus local feedback law, or an equivalent low-interaction decomposition.\n\n\"Decoupling\" has already carried too many meanings in this phase. The distinction is worth keeping, but the labels should make clear that behavioural dissociation does not imply structural separability.\n\n\nIf only one experiment can be done next, I still choose the matched-epsilon round-trip gate: `Phase 0.5` target materialisation, state-map regression, then the linear LQR/Hinf training gate.\n\nReason: the curl-field baseline is expected to be interpretable only in relation to a validated broad-epsilon arm. A null or gain-only curl result would be consistent with several stories: narrow objective, insufficient training, task mismatch, lack of trial-history learning, missing biomechanics, or no broad prior. It would not validate the epsilon machinery or establish that broad-class training can reproduce the analytical signature.\n\nThat said, if the curl-field baseline is genuinely cheap because existing machinery already supports it, I would run it in parallel with `Phase 0.5` as a non-blocking descriptive baseline. I would not put it before the epsilon gate as a decision gate. Its role is to sharpen the later contrast, not to decide whether the epsilon gate is worth doing.\n\nSo my centrality ranking is:\n\n- Must-do/blocker: cs_faithful analytical target + state-map/equivalence test + linear epsilon round-trip.\n- Must-do before strong scientific claims: same-task curl-vs-epsilon GRU contrast after the epsilon machinery is validated.\n- Nice-to-have/non-blocking: cheap curl-field baseline on the current production task, if it can be run without derailing the gate.\n- Defer: production-plant and delayed-reach bridge variants until the gate passes, except where needed to define the eventual clean contrast.\n\n\nI would soften one thing from my earlier framing: \"full-state epsilon is most likely to induce the cs2019 signature\" is still true for the cs2019 analytical model, but it should not be phrased as \"therefore it is the human-protocol-matched training condition.\" It is the model-matched broad-class condition.\n\nI would also retract any implied dismissal of the curl-field arm. Under the new framing it is essential, not because I expect it to produce the human speed signature, but because its failure or partial success defines what must be explained by broad-class training, priors, biomechanics, or architecture.\n\nI do not retract the cs_faithful-first recommendation, the state-map blocker, the multi-criterion linear gate, or the warning that fixed learned Delta-A flavor-B is a different game with a built-in slow-state incentive.\n\n\nThe brainstorming still needs a sharper definition of \"generalisation\" as an observable. I would not infer it from Delta v alone. A useful evaluation suite would include transfer across perturbation families: trained-on curl vs held-out curl magnitudes/directions, additive force pulses, full-state epsilon audit, velocity-dependent fields, state-channel perturbations, and induced-gain channels. Then \"generalisation\" means robustness transfer beyond the trained perturbation distribution.\n\nThe uncertainty context also needs to be specified. Humans experience phases/trial histories/instructions. A trained GRU is usually a fixed policy unless given a context/SISU input or trained as a learner across trials. Comparing \"uncertain\" vs \"baseline\" behaviour requires deciding whether this is between separately trained models, within one model conditioned on context, or trial-history adaptation. Those are scientifically different.\n\nThe curl-field arm needs protocol fidelity. Is it 20% perturbed trials? random signs? catch trials? perturbation active during movement only? Does the network know the block context? Is the evaluation on unperturbed trials after training or during mixed uncertainty? Those choices determine whether the arm is \"human protocol matched\" or just \"some curl training\".\n\nThe plan should also keep the cost/objective interpretation explicit. A speed increase can come from robust control, changed movement urgency, overshoot tolerance, energy weighting, or unstable training dynamics. The Phase 3 multi-criterion gate handles this for the analytical round-trip; the curl-vs-epsilon GRU contrast needs an analogous behavioural-cost audit.\n\nFinally, if the eventual outcome is \"curl GRU gain-only, epsilon GRU speed+gain\", that supports broad-class training as sufficient for the model, but it still does not prove humans generalise in that way. The honest conclusion would be narrower and stronger: broad adversary-class training induces the cs2019-like signature in GRUs; curl-distribution training does not under this task/objective; the human result therefore requires either broad prior/context, biomechanical coupling, a different objective, or a mechanism not captured by the GRU training setup.\n\nCo-authored-by: Codex (GPT-5) \u003ccodex@openai.com\u003e","files":null}]}